---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar.astro';

const post = {
  title: 'Getting Started with Go Concurrency',
  date: '2026-01-13',
  tags: ['Go', 'Concurrency', 'Backend'],
};

const formatDate = (dateString: string) => {
  const date = new Date(dateString);
  return date.toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' });
};
---

<Layout
  title={`${post.title} - Eben Bentley`}
  name="Eben Bentley"
  description="Learn the fundamentals of concurrent programming in Go using goroutines and channels. Explore patterns and best practices for building scalable applications."
>
  <Navbar name="Eben Bentley" currentPath="/blog" />

  <div class="container max-w-3xl mx-auto px-8 py-16 sm:px-4">
    <a href="/blog" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-accent hover:underline mb-8">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M15 19l-7-7 7-7" />
      </svg>
      Back to Blog
    </a>

    <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
        <h1 class="text-5xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">{post.title}</h1>

        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-text-secondary">
          <time datetime={post.date}>{formatDate(post.date)}</time>
          <span class="text-border">•</span>
          <div class="flex gap-2">
            {post.tags.map((tag) => (
              <span class="px-2 py-1 rounded-full bg-accent/10 text-accent text-sm font-medium">
                {tag}
              </span>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="border-t border-border pt-8 space-y-6 text-text-primary">
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Concurrency is one of Go's most powerful features, enabling developers to write efficient,
          scalable applications that can handle multiple tasks simultaneously. In this article, we'll
          explore the fundamentals of concurrent programming in Go.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">What are Goroutines?</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Goroutines are lightweight threads managed by the Go runtime. Unlike traditional OS threads,
          goroutines are extremely cheap to create and use minimal memory, making it practical to spawn
          thousands or even millions of them in a single application.
        </p>

        <pre class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm">func main() {
    go sayHello()
    time.Sleep(100 * time.Millisecond)
}

func sayHello() {
    fmt.Println("Hello from goroutine!")
}</code></pre>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Channels for Communication</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Channels are Go's way of allowing goroutines to communicate with each other and synchronize
          their execution. They provide a type-safe way to send and receive values between goroutines.
        </p>

        <pre class="bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm">ch := make(chan string)

go func() {
    ch <- "Hello from channel!"
}()

msg := <-ch
fmt.Println(msg)</code></pre>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Synchronization Primitives</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          The sync package provides essential synchronization primitives like WaitGroups, Mutexes, and
          RWMutexes. These tools help coordinate goroutines and protect shared resources from race conditions.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Best Practices</h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
          <li>Always close channels when you're done sending values</li>
          <li>Use buffered channels to prevent goroutine blocking when appropriate</li>
          <li>Avoid sharing memory by communicating; use channels instead of shared variables</li>
          <li>Use context for cancellation and timeouts in concurrent operations</li>
          <li>Be mindful of goroutine leaks and always ensure they terminate</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Conclusion</h2>
        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Mastering concurrency in Go opens up powerful possibilities for building high-performance
          applications. By understanding goroutines, channels, and synchronization primitives, you can
          write code that efficiently utilizes modern multi-core processors while remaining safe and maintainable.
        </p>

        <p class="leading-relaxed">
          Check out my <a href="https://github.com/Eben-Bentley/goroutines" class="text-accent hover:underline">goroutines repository</a> for
          practical examples and patterns demonstrating these concepts in action.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  article.prose {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  article.prose h2 {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  article.prose a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  article.prose a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  article.prose code {
    color: var(--text-primary);
    font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
  }

  article.prose ul li {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }
</style>
